messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}

HTTP methods acceptable for this endpoint (based on the code):
- all (all HTTP methods acceptable): false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The deleteConsumerPrintingSchema method is annotated with:
  @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", method = RequestMethod.DELETE)
  which explicitly exposes DELETE on the path /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}. Therefore DELETE = true.
- There is also a method editConsumerPrintingSchema annotated with:
  @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}", method = RequestMethod.PUT)
  exposing PUT on the same path. Therefore PUT = true.
- No method in the class has an explicit RequestMapping for HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, POST, GET or PATCH on /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas/{printingSchemaID}; accordingly those are marked false. (Note: there are GET and POST mappings in this controller, but they apply to /consumer/{consumerID}/printingschemas (no printingSchemaID) â€” they do not apply to the path with {printingSchemaID}.)
- I did not assume any framework-provided automatic handling (e.g., automatic HEAD or OPTIONS behavior); the results are determined only from the explicit @RequestMapping method attributes in the source code.
